I think the premise is to fine tune the model with really high quality data so that you can automate a big part of the workflow. You can still complement the rest of the work with ChatGPT-like general models. Both have to coexist. Also enterprises have valuable private data so they have specific requirements.

In reality you still need to land with a product to be able to collect high quality data to begin with. You can't really be an AI product with the single premise of AI in SaaS space. You'll get commodotized.

I think this comes down to data and training requirements at least for enterprise software. for midmarket SaaS tools, you need to regularly collect data (or implement a way to do RLHF within the tool) by building the common workflows to keep improving the fine tuned model.

Probably that's also why Google and Microsoft have big advantages here because they have access to a lot of workflows, including cross product ones and they can give a better experience with minimal vendor overhead.
